In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle events in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity =>
            {
                // runs when app is partially obscured
            })
            .OnStop(activity =>
            {
                // runs when app is no longer visible
            }));
#elif IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(app =>
            {
                // runs when app enters background
            }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional
- **Android**: `OnPause` (partially hidden) and `OnStop` (fully hidden) map to the standard `Activity` lifecycle
- **iOS**: `DidEnterBackground` maps to `UIApplicationDelegate.DidEnterBackground`
- Other events are available too (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`)
